snippet.textDisplay:
4:10 That bit about Roman architecture sounds a bit off to me as an archaeologist - did you mingle Roman with Romanesque and Classical?

There is ample evidence that many Roman buildings in Europe still stood upright in the Middle Ages and were used according to written sources (like some aquaeducts, temples turned to churches, theatres built into housing or fortresses).
Romanesque is a building style that came up in the early Middle Ages in the Italian and Frankish regions of Europe as a direct copy of Roman architecture. The time of Charlemagne is actually considered its own 'Carolingian renaissance', as he did a lot to further education, art and architecture based on the still existing classical tradition especially in his Italian realm.
snippet.textOriginal:
4:10 That bit about Roman architecture sounds a bit off to me as an archaeologist - did you mingle Roman with Romanesque and Classical?

There is ample evidence that many Roman buildings in Europe still stood upright in the Middle Ages and were used according to written sources (like some aquaeducts, temples turned to churches, theatres built into housing or fortresses).
Romanesque is a building style that came up in the early Middle Ages in the Italian and Frankish regions of Europe as a *direct* copy of Roman architecture. The time of Charlemagne is actually considered its own 'Carolingian renaissance', as he did a lot to further education, art and architecture based on the still existing classical tradition especially in his Italian realm.

snippet.textDisplay: In a sense the Middle Ages won't exist. In a few thousand years it will all be gelled together. Much like most people can't tell the difference between Egyptian history circa 3000 BC and Egyptian history circa1000 BC (while an ancient Alexandrian scholar probably could), future people won't be able to tell the difference between Europe circa 800 AD and Europe circa 1400. Even now most people would say of those times "uh, knights on horses, castles, crusades, Popes?" without being able to detail the Abbasid Caliphate, Charlemagne, the Byzantine Empire vs. The Black Death, the 100 Years War, and the fall of Constantinople. It just all kind of runs together. Take away the histories that time will eventually devour and it will.
